</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Small bowel tumors are rare and account for approximately 3% of all gastrointestinal tumors in the United States. The incidence of small bowel neoplasms is rising—in particular, there is a rising incidence of small bowel carcinoid tumors. This may in part be due to small bowel lesion identification in an increasing number of cross-sectional imaging studies performed for other indications as well as increased use of advanced imaging techniques to assess specifically for small bowel disease. Diagnosis is a challenge owing to nonspecific clinical manifestation, rare occurrence, and low index of clinical suspicion. Yet, various small bowel neoplasms have characteristic imaging features at CT and MRI when optimal distention of the small bowel is achieved, correlating well with features seen in gross specimens. Understanding the imaging features of small bowel neoplasms is important to improve the radiologist’s ability to diagnose and characterize small bowel neoplasms. Most small bowel tumors are clinically silent for long periods, and nearly half of the benign tumors are found incidentally during surgery or at cross-sectional imaging performed for other reasons. The authors review the imaging features of common benign and malignant small bowel neoplasms to aid the radiologist in diagnosis of small bowel tumors.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020200011">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020200011">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic" aria-label="Small bowel adenoma. Axial (a) and coronal (b) CT images with oral and intravenous contrast material show a round well-circumscribed filling defect (arrow) in the mid small bowel. The small bowel is mildly prominent proximal to the lesion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig1a.jpeg" height="1337" width="1619" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Small bowel adenoma. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> CT images with oral and intravenous contrast material show a round well-circumscribed filling defect (arrow) in the mid small bowel. The small bowel is mildly prominent proximal to the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic" aria-label="Small bowel adenoma. Axial (a) and coronal (b) CT images with oral and intravenous contrast material show a round well-circumscribed filling defect (arrow) in the mid small bowel. The small bowel is mildly prominent proximal to the lesion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig1b.jpeg" height="1337" width="1330" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Small bowel adenoma. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> CT images with oral and intravenous contrast material show a round well-circumscribed filling defect (arrow) in the mid small bowel. The small bowel is mildly prominent proximal to the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic" aria-label="Jejunal hamartoma in a pediatric patient with a history of Peutz-Jeghers syndrome. Axial (a) and sagittal oblique (b) images from contrast-enhanced CT enterography show an enhancing intraluminal mass (arrow) in the proximal jejunum."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig2a.jpeg" height="1292" width="1588" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Jejunal hamartoma in a pediatric patient with a history of Peutz-Jeghers syndrome. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal oblique <b>(b)</b> images from contrast-enhanced CT enterography show an enhancing intraluminal mass (arrow) in the proximal jejunum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic" aria-label="Jejunal hamartoma in a pediatric patient with a history of Peutz-Jeghers syndrome. Axial (a) and sagittal oblique (b) images from contrast-enhanced CT enterography show an enhancing intraluminal mass (arrow) in the proximal jejunum."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig2b.jpeg" height="1292" width="1360" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Jejunal hamartoma in a pediatric patient with a history of Peutz-Jeghers syndrome. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal oblique <b>(b)</b> images from contrast-enhanced CT enterography show an enhancing intraluminal mass (arrow) in the proximal jejunum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="Jejunal lipoma. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-circumscribed, smooth, homogeneous fat attenuation mass (arrow) in the jejunum. (b) Fluoroscopic spot image from an SBFT study shows a well-defined intraluminal mass (arrow) in the jejunum expanding the lumen. The overlying mucosa is intact, as the lesion arises in the submucosa."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig3a.jpeg" height="1250" width="1524" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Jejunal lipoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-circumscribed, smooth, homogeneous fat attenuation mass (arrow) in the jejunum. <b>(b)</b> Fluoroscopic spot image from an SBFT study shows a well-defined intraluminal mass (arrow) in the jejunum expanding the lumen. The overlying mucosa is intact, as the lesion arises in the submucosa.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="Jejunal lipoma. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-circumscribed, smooth, homogeneous fat attenuation mass (arrow) in the jejunum. (b) Fluoroscopic spot image from an SBFT study shows a well-defined intraluminal mass (arrow) in the jejunum expanding the lumen. The overlying mucosa is intact, as the lesion arises in the submucosa."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig3b.jpeg" height="1250" width="1425" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Jejunal lipoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-circumscribed, smooth, homogeneous fat attenuation mass (arrow) in the jejunum. <b>(b)</b> Fluoroscopic spot image from an SBFT study shows a well-defined intraluminal mass (arrow) in the jejunum expanding the lumen. The overlying mucosa is intact, as the lesion arises in the submucosa.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic" aria-label="Benign duodenal GIST. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small, well-defined, heterogeneously enhancing mass (arrows) in the distal descending duodenum. (b, c) Axial (b) and coronal (c) T2-weighted MR images show that the mass (arrows) is mildly heterogeneous and mildly hyperintense, located just below the pancreatic duct, and growing partially exophytically."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig4a.jpeg" height="1124" width="1429" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Benign duodenal GIST. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small, well-defined, heterogeneously enhancing mass (arrows) in the distal descending duodenum. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR images show that the mass (arrows) is mildly heterogeneous and mildly hyperintense, located just below the pancreatic duct, and growing partially exophytically.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="Benign duodenal GIST. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small, well-defined, heterogeneously enhancing mass (arrows) in the distal descending duodenum. (b, c) Axial (b) and coronal (c) T2-weighted MR images show that the mass (arrows) is mildly heterogeneous and mildly hyperintense, located just below the pancreatic duct, and growing partially exophytically."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig4b.jpeg" height="1124" width="1501" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Benign duodenal GIST. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small, well-defined, heterogeneously enhancing mass (arrows) in the distal descending duodenum. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR images show that the mass (arrows) is mildly heterogeneous and mildly hyperintense, located just below the pancreatic duct, and growing partially exophytically.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic" aria-label="Benign duodenal GIST. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small, well-defined, heterogeneously enhancing mass (arrows) in the distal descending duodenum. (b, c) Axial (b) and coronal (c) T2-weighted MR images show that the mass (arrows) is mildly heterogeneous and mildly hyperintense, located just below the pancreatic duct, and growing partially exophytically."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig4c.jpeg" height="1124" width="1423" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Benign duodenal GIST. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small, well-defined, heterogeneously enhancing mass (arrows) in the distal descending duodenum. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR images show that the mass (arrows) is mildly heterogeneous and mildly hyperintense, located just below the pancreatic duct, and growing partially exophytically.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Benign ileal GIST. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-defined, heterogeneous, exophytic mass (arrow) in the ileum."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig5.jpeg" height="1352" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Benign ileal GIST. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-defined, heterogeneous, exophytic mass (arrow) in the ileum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="Jejunal GIST. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous, hypoenhancing, exophytic GIST (arrow) in the proximal jejunum. The mass has peripheral calcifications."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig6.jpeg" height="1328" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Jejunal GIST. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous, hypoenhancing, exophytic GIST (arrow) in the proximal jejunum. The mass has peripheral calcifications.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="Jejunal diverticulitis. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image shows an inflammatory mass (arrow) in the left midabdomen. There is mild jejunal wall thickening with prominent soft-tissue stranding and several outpouchings containing gas (diverticula). (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows complete resolution of the inflammatory changes involving the jejunum (arrow). Numerous discrete diverticula are now seen."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig7a.jpeg" height="1137" width="1509" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Jejunal diverticulitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows an inflammatory mass (arrow) in the left midabdomen. There is mild jejunal wall thickening with prominent soft-tissue stranding and several outpouchings containing gas (diverticula). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows complete resolution of the inflammatory changes involving the jejunum (arrow). Numerous discrete diverticula are now seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="Jejunal diverticulitis. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image shows an inflammatory mass (arrow) in the left midabdomen. There is mild jejunal wall thickening with prominent soft-tissue stranding and several outpouchings containing gas (diverticula). (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows complete resolution of the inflammatory changes involving the jejunum (arrow). Numerous discrete diverticula are now seen."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig7b.jpeg" height="1135" width="1637" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Jejunal diverticulitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows an inflammatory mass (arrow) in the left midabdomen. There is mild jejunal wall thickening with prominent soft-tissue stranding and several outpouchings containing gas (diverticula). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows complete resolution of the inflammatory changes involving the jejunum (arrow). Numerous discrete diverticula are now seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Meckel diverticulum with small bowel obstruction. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a blind-ending fluid- and debris-filled masslike abnormality (arrows). This can be seen to communicate with the ileum and represents a Meckel diverticulum. Note the dilated small bowel leading to the partially obstructing diverticulum."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig8.jpeg" height="1464" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Meckel diverticulum with small bowel obstruction. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a blind-ending fluid- and debris-filled masslike abnormality (arrows). This can be seen to communicate with the ileum and represents a Meckel diverticulum. Note the dilated small bowel leading to the partially obstructing diverticulum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Small bowel hematoma with obstruction in a patient with hemophilia. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a focal segment of ileum with marked circumferential wall thickening (arrow) and surrounding inflammatory change. The mural thickening is mildly hyperattenuating, and there is associated luminal narrowing causing partial obstruction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig9.jpeg" height="1335" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Small bowel hematoma with obstruction in a patient with hemophilia. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a focal segment of ileum with marked circumferential wall thickening (arrow) and surrounding inflammatory change. The mural thickening is mildly hyperattenuating, and there is associated luminal narrowing causing partial obstruction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic" aria-label="Primary adenocarcinoma of the duodenojejunal junction. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an ill-defined mass with irregular and heterogeneous wall thickening (arrow) at the duodenojejunal junction. There is associated irregular luminal narrowing. (b) Spot image from upper gastrointestinal study shows an annular “apple core” lesion (arrows) without obstruction. D = duodenum, S = stomach."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig10a.jpeg" height="1220" width="1719" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Primary adenocarcinoma of the duodenojejunal junction. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an ill-defined mass with irregular and heterogeneous wall thickening (arrow) at the duodenojejunal junction. There is associated irregular luminal narrowing. <b>(b)</b> Spot image from upper gastrointestinal study shows an annular “apple core” lesion (arrows) without obstruction. <i>D</i> = duodenum, <i>S</i> = stomach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic" aria-label="Primary adenocarcinoma of the duodenojejunal junction. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an ill-defined mass with irregular and heterogeneous wall thickening (arrow) at the duodenojejunal junction. There is associated irregular luminal narrowing. (b) Spot image from upper gastrointestinal study shows an annular “apple core” lesion (arrows) without obstruction. D = duodenum, S = stomach."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig10b.jpeg" height="1220" width="1230" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Primary adenocarcinoma of the duodenojejunal junction. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an ill-defined mass with irregular and heterogeneous wall thickening (arrow) at the duodenojejunal junction. There is associated irregular luminal narrowing. <b>(b)</b> Spot image from upper gastrointestinal study shows an annular “apple core” lesion (arrows) without obstruction. <i>D</i> = duodenum, <i>S</i> = stomach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic" aria-label="Jejunal adenocarcinoma. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous soft-tissue mass (arrows) in the proximal jejunum. There is associated edema with soft-tissue stranding. (b) Spot image from SBFT study shows an ulcerated mass with irregular luminal narrowing (arrows). D = duodenum, S = stomach."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig11a.jpeg" height="1260" width="1525" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Jejunal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous soft-tissue mass (arrows) in the proximal jejunum. There is associated edema with soft-tissue stranding. <b>(b)</b> Spot image from SBFT study shows an ulcerated mass with irregular luminal narrowing (arrows). <i>D</i> = duodenum, <i>S</i> = stomach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic" aria-label="Jejunal adenocarcinoma. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous soft-tissue mass (arrows) in the proximal jejunum. There is associated edema with soft-tissue stranding. (b) Spot image from SBFT study shows an ulcerated mass with irregular luminal narrowing (arrows). D = duodenum, S = stomach."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig11b.jpeg" height="1260" width="1426" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Jejunal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous soft-tissue mass (arrows) in the proximal jejunum. There is associated edema with soft-tissue stranding. <b>(b)</b> Spot image from SBFT study shows an ulcerated mass with irregular luminal narrowing (arrows). <i>D</i> = duodenum, <i>S</i> = stomach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic" aria-label="Small bowel obstruction due to a midjejunal adenocarcinoma. Coronal (a) and axial (b) contrast-enhanced CT images show an annular soft-tissue mass (arrows) with marked dilatation of small bowel proximal to the mass. Note the overhanging margins on the coronal image."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig12a.jpeg" height="1436" width="1431" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Small bowel obstruction due to a midjejunal adenocarcinoma. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show an annular soft-tissue mass (arrows) with marked dilatation of small bowel proximal to the mass. Note the overhanging margins on the coronal image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Small bowel obstruction due to a midjejunal adenocarcinoma. Coronal (a) and axial (b) contrast-enhanced CT images show an annular soft-tissue mass (arrows) with marked dilatation of small bowel proximal to the mass. Note the overhanging margins on the coronal image."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig12b.jpeg" height="1436" width="1517" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Small bowel obstruction due to a midjejunal adenocarcinoma. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show an annular soft-tissue mass (arrows) with marked dilatation of small bowel proximal to the mass. Note the overhanging margins on the coronal image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Jejunal adenocarcinoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large, annular and irregular, ulcerated soft-tissue mass with asymmetric wall thickening (arrows) in the jejunum. Note the associated local spread and regional adenopathy (arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig13.jpeg" height="1454" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Jejunal adenocarcinoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large, annular and irregular, ulcerated soft-tissue mass with asymmetric wall thickening (arrows) in the jejunum. Note the associated local spread and regional adenopathy (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic" aria-label="Malignant duodenal GIST. (a, b) Axial (a) and coronal (b) T2-weighted MR images show a large bulky mass with moderately increased signal intensity (arrows) arising in the duodenum. The mass results in biliary duct dilatation (arrowhead in b). (c) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image with fat suppression shows avid enhancement of the mass (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig14a.jpeg" height="1289" width="1848" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Malignant duodenal GIST. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a large bulky mass with moderately increased signal intensity (arrows) arising in the duodenum. The mass results in biliary duct dilatation (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image with fat suppression shows avid enhancement of the mass (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic" aria-label="Malignant duodenal GIST. (a, b) Axial (a) and coronal (b) T2-weighted MR images show a large bulky mass with moderately increased signal intensity (arrows) arising in the duodenum. The mass results in biliary duct dilatation (arrowhead in b). (c) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image with fat suppression shows avid enhancement of the mass (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig14b.jpeg" height="1289" width="1299" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Malignant duodenal GIST. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a large bulky mass with moderately increased signal intensity (arrows) arising in the duodenum. The mass results in biliary duct dilatation (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image with fat suppression shows avid enhancement of the mass (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic" aria-label="Malignant duodenal GIST. (a, b) Axial (a) and coronal (b) T2-weighted MR images show a large bulky mass with moderately increased signal intensity (arrows) arising in the duodenum. The mass results in biliary duct dilatation (arrowhead in b). (c) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image with fat suppression shows avid enhancement of the mass (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig14c.jpeg" height="1248" width="1798" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Malignant duodenal GIST. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a large bulky mass with moderately increased signal intensity (arrows) arising in the duodenum. The mass results in biliary duct dilatation (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image with fat suppression shows avid enhancement of the mass (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic" aria-label="Malignant jejunal GIST. Axial (a) and coronal (b) contrast-enhanced CT images show a large, bulky, lobulated heterogeneous mass (arrows) with areas of necrosis arising from the jejunum. Note the peritoneal thickening and nodularity (arrowheads), which is due to peritoneal spread of disease."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig15a.jpeg" height="1186" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Malignant jejunal GIST. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a large, bulky, lobulated heterogeneous mass (arrows) with areas of necrosis arising from the jejunum. Note the peritoneal thickening and nodularity (arrowheads), which is due to peritoneal spread of disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="Malignant jejunal GIST. Axial (a) and coronal (b) contrast-enhanced CT images show a large, bulky, lobulated heterogeneous mass (arrows) with areas of necrosis arising from the jejunum. Note the peritoneal thickening and nodularity (arrowheads), which is due to peritoneal spread of disease."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig15b.jpeg" height="1186" width="1373" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Malignant jejunal GIST. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a large, bulky, lobulated heterogeneous mass (arrows) with areas of necrosis arising from the jejunum. Note the peritoneal thickening and nodularity (arrowheads), which is due to peritoneal spread of disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic" aria-label="Distal ileal carcinoid tumor. (a) Fluoroscopic spot image from SBFT study shows a small filling defect (arrows) in the distal ileum. The filling defect was fixed and persistent during the examination. Pathologic analysis demonstrated a primary carcinoid tumor. (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in another patient shows a spiculated, desmoplastic, mesenteric soft-tissue mass containing calcifications (arrows). The mass was due to metastatic carcinoid tumor."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig16a.jpeg" height="1259" width="1136" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Distal ileal carcinoid tumor. <b>(a)</b> Fluoroscopic spot image from SBFT study shows a small filling defect (arrows) in the distal ileum. The filling defect was fixed and persistent during the examination. Pathologic analysis demonstrated a primary carcinoid tumor. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in another patient shows a spiculated, desmoplastic, mesenteric soft-tissue mass containing calcifications (arrows). The mass was due to metastatic carcinoid tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic" aria-label="Distal ileal carcinoid tumor. (a) Fluoroscopic spot image from SBFT study shows a small filling defect (arrows) in the distal ileum. The filling defect was fixed and persistent during the examination. Pathologic analysis demonstrated a primary carcinoid tumor. (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in another patient shows a spiculated, desmoplastic, mesenteric soft-tissue mass containing calcifications (arrows). The mass was due to metastatic carcinoid tumor."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig16b.jpeg" height="1259" width="1813" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Distal ileal carcinoid tumor. <b>(a)</b> Fluoroscopic spot image from SBFT study shows a small filling defect (arrows) in the distal ileum. The filling defect was fixed and persistent during the examination. Pathologic analysis demonstrated a primary carcinoid tumor. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in another patient shows a spiculated, desmoplastic, mesenteric soft-tissue mass containing calcifications (arrows). The mass was due to metastatic carcinoid tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic" aria-label="Ileal carcinoid tumor with adjacent mesenteric mass. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show a small filling defect (arrow in b) in a segment of opacified ileum. The primary lesion is contiguous with a mesenteric soft-tissue mass (arrow in a)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig17a.jpeg" height="1203" width="1455" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Ileal carcinoid tumor with adjacent mesenteric mass. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show a small filling defect (arrow in <b>b</b>) in a segment of opacified ileum. The primary lesion is contiguous with a mesenteric soft-tissue mass (arrow in <b>a</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic" aria-label="Ileal carcinoid tumor with adjacent mesenteric mass. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show a small filling defect (arrow in b) in a segment of opacified ileum. The primary lesion is contiguous with a mesenteric soft-tissue mass (arrow in a)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig17b.jpeg" height="1203" width="1494" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Ileal carcinoid tumor with adjacent mesenteric mass. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show a small filling defect (arrow in <b>b</b>) in a segment of opacified ileum. The primary lesion is contiguous with a mesenteric soft-tissue mass (arrow in <b>a</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic" aria-label="Ileal carcinoid tumor with desmoplastic reaction and small bowel obstruction. Coronal (a) and sagittal (b) contrast-enhanced CT images show an enhancing lesion in the ileum (arrows) that extends into the mesentery, pulling and tethering adjacent small bowel and causing obstruction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig18a.jpeg" height="1532" width="1535" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Ileal carcinoid tumor with desmoplastic reaction and small bowel obstruction. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show an enhancing lesion in the ileum (arrows) that extends into the mesentery, pulling and tethering adjacent small bowel and causing obstruction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic" aria-label="Ileal carcinoid tumor with desmoplastic reaction and small bowel obstruction. Coronal (a) and sagittal (b) contrast-enhanced CT images show an enhancing lesion in the ileum (arrows) that extends into the mesentery, pulling and tethering adjacent small bowel and causing obstruction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig18b.jpeg" height="1532" width="1423" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Ileal carcinoid tumor with desmoplastic reaction and small bowel obstruction. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show an enhancing lesion in the ileum (arrows) that extends into the mesentery, pulling and tethering adjacent small bowel and causing obstruction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic" aria-label="Ileal lymphoma (pseudoaneurysmal form) with lymphomatosis. Axial nonenhanced CT image shows extensive masslike soft-tissue wall thickening of an ileal segment (arrows). Despite the extensive soft tissue, the opacified bowel lumen is actually widened and there is no obstruction. Note the confluent omental soft tissue (arrowheads) and the small amount of complex fluid in the right paracolic gutter due to lymphomatosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig19.jpeg" height="1477" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Ileal lymphoma (pseudoaneurysmal form) with lymphomatosis. Axial nonenhanced CT image shows extensive masslike soft-tissue wall thickening of an ileal segment (arrows). Despite the extensive soft tissue, the opacified bowel lumen is actually widened and there is no obstruction. Note the confluent omental soft tissue (arrowheads) and the small amount of complex fluid in the right paracolic gutter due to lymphomatosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic" aria-label="Multifocal small bowel lymphoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show ileocolic intussusception (arrows in a) due to small bowel polypoid lesions and adenopathy. The largest mesenteric node is seen slightly more inferior in the right lower quadrant (arrowhead in b). There is nodularity in the adjacent ileum. There is a well-defined polypoid mass (arrow in b) in the distal jejunum in the left midabdomen. There was also associated short-segment intussusception (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig20a.jpeg" height="1058" width="1501" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Multifocal small bowel lymphoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show ileocolic intussusception (arrows in <b>a</b>) due to small bowel polypoid lesions and adenopathy. The largest mesenteric node is seen slightly more inferior in the right lower quadrant (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). There is nodularity in the adjacent ileum. There is a well-defined polypoid mass (arrow in <b>b</b>) in the distal jejunum in the left midabdomen. There was also associated short-segment intussusception (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic" aria-label="Multifocal small bowel lymphoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show ileocolic intussusception (arrows in a) due to small bowel polypoid lesions and adenopathy. The largest mesenteric node is seen slightly more inferior in the right lower quadrant (arrowhead in b). There is nodularity in the adjacent ileum. There is a well-defined polypoid mass (arrow in b) in the distal jejunum in the left midabdomen. There was also associated short-segment intussusception (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig20b.jpeg" height="1058" width="1653" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Multifocal small bowel lymphoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show ileocolic intussusception (arrows in <b>a</b>) due to small bowel polypoid lesions and adenopathy. The largest mesenteric node is seen slightly more inferior in the right lower quadrant (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). There is nodularity in the adjacent ileum. There is a well-defined polypoid mass (arrow in <b>b</b>) in the distal jejunum in the left midabdomen. There was also associated short-segment intussusception (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic" aria-label="Ileal lymphoma: cavitary form. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large lobulated exophytic mass (arrows) arising from a distal ileal loop. The mass has central hypoattenuation due to necrosis and communicates with the bowel lumen. I = ileum."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig21.jpeg" height="1580" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. Ileal lymphoma: cavitary form. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large lobulated exophytic mass (arrows) arising from a distal ileal loop. The mass has central hypoattenuation due to necrosis and communicates with the bowel lumen. <i>I</i> = ileum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic" aria-label="Metastatic disease to jejunum from breast cancer. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large lobulated soft-tissue mass (arrows) involving the proximal jejunum. The lesion is annular, and there is luminal narrowing with dilatation of the duodenum (D) owing to the partial obstruction. Note the tumor implant along the abdominal wall (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig22.jpeg" height="1320" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. Metastatic disease to jejunum from breast cancer. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large lobulated soft-tissue mass (arrows) involving the proximal jejunum. The lesion is annular, and there is luminal narrowing with dilatation of the duodenum <i>(D)</i> owing to the partial obstruction. Note the tumor implant along the abdominal wall (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic" aria-label="Metastatic disease to jejunum from melanoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an ulcerative and polypoid intraluminal mass (arrowheads) in the jejunum with associated necrotic adenopathy (arrows). There were additional polypoid small bowel lesions, some of which had associated intussusception (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig23.jpeg" height="1448" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. Metastatic disease to jejunum from melanoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an ulcerative and polypoid intraluminal mass (arrowheads) in the jejunum with associated necrotic adenopathy (arrows). There were additional polypoid small bowel lesions, some of which had associated intussusception (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal leiomyosarcoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large, heterogeneous, partially necrotic mass (white arrows) arising from the duodenum (black arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200011/asset/images/large/rg.2020200011.fig24.jpeg" height="1373" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span>. Duodenal leiomyosarcoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large, heterogeneous, partially necrotic mass (white arrows) arising from the duodenum (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200011&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Siegel RL, Miller KD, Jemal A. Cancer statistics, 2016. <em>CA Cancer J Clin</em> 2016;66(1):7–30.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.3322/caac.21332">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26742998/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Cancer+statistics%2C+2016&amp;author=RL+Siegel&amp;author=KD+Miller&amp;author=A+Jemal&amp;publication_year=2016&amp;journal=CA+Cancer+J+Clin&amp;pages=7-30&amp;doi=10.3322%2Fcaac.21332&amp;pmid=26742998">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Bilimoria KY, Bentrem DJ,